Fanatastic

Target IP:

Scanning


There are two ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 3000: HTTP

The target is running Grafana application, as shown above on this port. Spraying default credentials, such as admin:admin, against the login page did not work.


Running whatweb on this port shows the target is running Grafana 8.3.0 application. And apparently this application is vulnerable to LFI.

Exploitation


Using searchsploit, I saved a copy of the working exploit for the application version on my local machine and ran it against the target machine using the command python3 50581.py -H http://192.168.170.181:3000. I was able to succesfully read the /etc/passwd file on the target machine. Using this file, I identified a user called sysadmin; however, I was unable to read their SSH key.


Using the same exploit, I read the /etc/grafana/grafana.ini file. But admin:admin does not work.



I downloaded the grafana.db that contains the credentials of the users on the target machine to my machine. And then I used SQLite to read the database file. I obtained the hash anBneWFNQ2z+IDGhz3a7wxaqjimuglSXTeMvhbvsveZwVzreNJSw+hsV4w== for the user sysadmin.


I found the resource above with the go code to decrypt the password I retrieved from the grafana.db. I used the code to decrypt and obtain the password SuperSecureP@ssw0rd for sysadmin.


Now I have a foothold on the target machine using SSH with the credentials sysadmin:SuperSecureP@ssw0rd.

Privilege Escalation


The user sysadmin is in the group disk. This allows the user to have access to files with root privileges. The partition /dev/sda2 is high in size, so I debugged this using the command debugfs /dev/sda2. Then I accessed the SSH key of root. I coped this key to my local machine.


Then I used this key to SSH into the target machine. Now I have a root shell.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine.


The proof.txt flag once I SSHed into the target machine using the SSH key of user root.
